ociety that has grown accustomed to being misunderstood. In doing so, he argues that the values uniting Quebeckers – their common sense, courtesy, concern for the downtrodden, aversion to conflict, and mild form of nationalism, linked to a firm refusal to be homogenized by globalization – make them the most "Canadian" of all Canadians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aQuebec.  aclimate change.  adiversity.  aefficiency.  afairness.  aidentity.  aimmigration.  asocial policy.  asolidarity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753075440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487530754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487530754.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles